{"title_page": "Stanton Heck", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Stanton Heck\n| image       = A Perfect Crime (1921) - Ad 2.jpg\n| caption     = Heck (right) in film promotion in<br>''[[Wid's Daily]]'', 1921\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1877|1|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], USA\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1929|12|16|1877|1|8}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], USA\n| yearsactive = 1918-1928\n| othername   = Stanley Heck\n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n\n'''Stanton Heck''' (January 8, 1877 &ndash; December 16, 1929), was an American actor of the [[silent film|silent era]]. He appeared in 50 films between 1918 and 1928. Earlier in his career, he appeared on stage in musicals such as 1906's ''[[A Parisian Model]]''.<ref name=\"drammirror\">(December 8, 1906). [http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror%201906%20May-Apr%201907%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror%201906%20May-Apr%201907%20Grayscale%20-%200789.pdf At the Theatres], ''New York Dramatic Mirror'', p. 3 (Heck in cast list)</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Broadway Bill (1918 film)|Broadway Bill]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[The Landloper]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[He's in Again]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Unexpected Places (1918 film)|Unexpected Places]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Hitting the High Spots]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[The Hawk's Trail]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[One-Thing-at-a-Time O'Day]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Easy to Make Money]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Pink Tights]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The Money Changers]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[A Perfect Crime]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[The Power of a Lie]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[Man's Size]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Hearts Aflame (film)|Hearts Aflame]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[The Lone Star Ranger (1923 film)|The Lone Star Ranger]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[The Woman on the Jury]]'' (1924)\n* ''[[White Man (film)|White Man]]'' (1924)\n* ''[[One Law for the Woman]]'' (1924)\n* ''[[Soft Shoes]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Silent Sanderson]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[The Mystic]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Old Clothes]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[The Fighting Demon]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Driftin' Thru]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[Rustlers' Ranch]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[The Gentle Cyclone]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[Her Honor, the Governor]]'' (1926)\n* ''[[The Branded Sombrero]]'' (1928)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Stanton Heck}}\n*{{IMDb name|0373008}}\n*{{ibdb name|67787}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heck, Stanton}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Delaware]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n\n\n{{US-film-actor-1870s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Stanton Heck\n| image       = A Perfect Crime (1921) - Ad 2.jpg\n| caption     = Heck (right) in film promotion in<br>''[[Wid's Daily]]'', 1921\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1877|1|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], USA\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1929|12|16|1877|1|8}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], USA\n| yearsactive = 1918-1928\n| othername   = Stanley Heck\n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n\n'''Stanton Heck''' (January 8, 1877 &ndash; December 16, 1929), was an American actor of the [[silent film|silent era]]. He appeared in 50 films between 1918 and 1928. Earlier in his career, he appeared on stage in musicals such as 1906's ''[[A Parisian Model]]''.<ref name=\"drammirror\">(December 8, 1906). [http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror%201906%20May-Apr%201907%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Dramatic%20Mirror%201906%20May-Apr%201907%20Gray